segments.text: Bob Collins, who served as a member of the SEAL Squad in Vietnam from the years 1971 to 1974.
Okay, Mr. Collins, you served in Vietnam from 1971 until 1974.
Can you tell me why you volunteered and what influences initiated you to volunteer?
Well, I think
Part of the main reason is my grandfather was in the Navy and my father was in the Navy.
I had several uncles that were in the Navy.
That's why I went Navy.
The draft really didn't come into play.
I had volunteered a year before I even graduated from high school, so that didn't have any influence.
With all of what was going on in Vietnam,
I guess the fear of living under a communistic rule was the biggest fear.
When you're in high school, most of the time you don't think about those things.
But Vietnam was becoming real relevant to us, the guys that were in high school.
And we started thinking about it.
I just didn't feel like living, even hearing and reading what I had read about communism, I didn't feel like living under that setting and whatever I felt like that I could do to combat that was...
Okay.
There were a lot of protests going on during that time also around 1970.
How did you regard the protests?
Well, when I was...
I really didn't pay any attention to them until I got to Vietnam.
And we would read about them in Stars and Stripes, from letters that we got from home about how this... And mainly it was college students on the campuses rioting and protesting for our benefit.
And I...

a lot of us had the attitude is how could they know without being there and knowing what our thoughts and our feelings were how could they sit over here on a college campus and riot for something that they knew nothing about you know we felt like you know coming back and knocking a few heads trying to get them to understand that we were there fighting for them so that they could be free to do what they were doing you know if it wasn't for the guys
that have fought in all the wars, we would probably be under a socialist-type government or a communistic government.
And they wouldn't have the freedom to do that.
But yet, they were over here rioting against the liberties that we were trying to supply them with or to keep them with.
It made us mad.

From the time you volunteered until the day you arrived in Vietnam, describe to me what type of training or education you received about the Vietnamese people, their religion, their country in general, and just basically what training you received, military, etc.
Well, that's where I really came to an appreciation of the Navy is you sit through...
daytime classes.
I mean, you go through eight hours over the class a day in the classroom setting.
And then you do, or we had to go through jungle tactic training, where it got us used to fighting in jungle.
Where was that training held?
In San Diego.
Well, along the coast of San Diego and Mexico.
We used to have to, every morning you go out and your CO is out there.
And there's a raft that weighs about 300 pounds.
And so you have to put it up on your shoulders and carry it down to the beach.
But it's weird as he's sitting in it.
And he's yelling at you and screaming at you.
But everything that they did, you know, they were real tough.
But because of their toughness, it helped keep us alive.
Well, what I was asking you earlier also is, did you receive any type of education about the Vietnamese people or their religion or anything?
Did you know anything about it before you got there?
Not really.
That was not our job.
That was for the diplomats.
Our job was to be an aggressor and get a job done.
We weren't there to try to further relations with the North Vietnamese people.
We were there to do a job.
whether it was to blow up a bridge or whether it was to get secret documents or to kidnap or to assassinate.
We were there to do a job and it was not a diplomatic job.
It was a military job.
Okay.
Can you describe for me a little bit about what a SEAL is and what it took to become one, how your team worked and what your role was as a member of that team?
Well, I was, the SEALs are,
I would say the most unique fighting group in the world.
There's an aggressor squad with the British, I understand now.
They have an aggressor company that are basically about the same as the SEALs.
The SEALs are the frogmen.
I don't know if you've ever seen any movies about the frogmen and what they did.
or do in military operations, but we worked in four-man teams, and each individual had a job to do.
This is the way it was set up with our team.
I was a protector.
I was there to, or we all really
Like when you hit the beach, each man turns his back toward the other one.
So you have a perimeter.
You got each man looking out.
And you go in like that.
And you're each protecting each other.
But in the setting of explosives or setting a perimeter watch, that's where I was called a protector.
And I would make sure that the rest of the team was able to get
away with whatever we were sent to do.
What about the other members?
What were their jobs?
Well, you have an explosives man.
If you're going in to blow up a bridge, you have a setter, which would set the explosives, and then a timer.
This guy would go and set timers.
What was the fourth man?
Like, I would stay on the outer perimeter, and the other guy would stay on the inside.
If I got wiped out, well, then there would still be one more man to protect it.
The main objective was just do the mission, get the mission accomplished.
And if it was, they would have to go through two of us to take out the explosives men.
So it was a lot of what
A lot of the real detailed stuff, it would take probably hours to tell you what exactly we did and how we did it.
Even on a mission where we would have to go in and take someone prisoner, a high ranking officer or whatever,
Our training was a lot more extensive than any other area, because we went on missions in North Vietnam only.
We didn't go to South Vietnam.
So the training, I
I guess I would go through it again if I had to.
It's not something that I would just like to do every day, though, because it was pretty rough.
Describe for me what a usual day would be like.
Well, it all depends on the day.
Normally,
Are you talking about basic training, or are you talking about in Vietnam?
In Vietnam.
In Vietnam.
It's a 24-hour day.
When we go on a mission, you don't sleep.
You don't rest until your mission's accomplished.
I remember one mission that we went on lasted about 36 hours.
That was a normal day.
So you really can't set it in a setting of a day.
This is what my daily work was.
Because each thing that we were set to do was so individualistic.
It was in a setting of its own.
Whether it was to go into the hardest
The hardest one was the assassinations, when we were sent in to eliminate one person in particular.
Such as?
Well, there was a...
I wish I could remember his name.
I can't remember his name.
Probably good that I can't remember his name.
There was a colonel that was in charge of tactical in the North Vietnam.
I can't remember if it was a tank.
We were sent in to get this guy.
He was a North Vietnamese guy?
Yeah.
That's all.
That's all that we dealt with was North Vietnamese.
The only time I saw South Vietnamese was when I was in the hospital.
That's the only time I saw South Vietnamese.
But the planning of trying to get to one person, especially when they're so well protected,
Because these guys were really well protected.
Sometimes it would take days for us to... We'd have to burrow in sometimes and stay for 24, 48 hours in a hole somewhere just waiting to have the opportunity.
Because we had to go in not only with the idea of getting this guy, but with the idea of getting out.
And it was not a suicide mission for us.
because we wanted to stay alive too.
But the objective was to get this guy and to get out alive.
So sometimes it would take four days to get to somebody that we were sent at.
What else was a normal day besides assassinations?
Stealing documents.
I guess the easiest things to do was to blow things up.
Such as?
Well, a bridge across a river where they're transporting weapons or food or whatever to their front lines.
No.
Basically,
Got to understand that the North Vietnamese were probably the best jungle fighters ever, ever, ever.
And so they could construct a bridge in 12 hours.
We could blow it up at night when they were transporting stuff.
And by the next evening, it would be right back up again.
And a lot of times it was just made out of heavy bamboo.
But it was made well enough.
We have CVs, construction builders, in our services.
But these guys could just go through the jungle and construct bridges made out of bamboo better than some of our steel bridges.
You could drive tanks across them.
So it was always a constant.
blow this up, blow that up, get rid of this.
We could stop their supply line for just a small amount of time, it was good.
Did you take prisoners very often?
Only the ones we were sent to get.
You took a prisoner or shot them?
Who?
The people we were after?
Yeah.
If we were sent to get them, we never lost anybody we were sent in to get.
If we were sent to take them prisoner, we took them prisoner.
If we were sent to kill them, then we did.
If we look at our losses in Vietnam, the 55,000 men, that's not even close to the price that the North Vietnamese paid.
And I think that's what gets to me the most is we cry over the 55,000 men.
But the idea, the whole, I don't know, the whole American idea seemed to have been lost.
We just stopped wanting to win and to stop them.
And eventually, they won out.
And that is the most degrading thing of all.
When we went in, we should have gone in to get the job done.
In World War II, when they were going in to free Paris or Rome or to really go into Germany itself,
Their attitude, their idea in the American people was to stamp out the aggressiveness of Hitler.
And we as an American people have just seemed to have lost that.
We don't have that idea anymore.
What sort of losses did your SEAL team take?
Well, of all the time I was there,
We lost one man for hearing problems.
And we lost one CO, a commanding officer.
And we lost one other all the time that I was there.
Two of them were killed and one of them was sent home?
Mm-hmm.
OK.
How much did your training help in your actual performance of duty?
Kept me alive more than once.
If it hadn't been, I think if it hadn't been for the training, I ran into a booby trap one time.
And if it hadn't been for the training, I probably would have been
The whole idea behind booby traps in Vietnam was not to kill you.
It was just to maim you.
And I hit one that was supposed to come up into my face.
It was bamboo strips.
And because of the alertness and the quickness that you learn in training,
I was able to protect myself.
I had 408 stitches in my arms where the bamboo cut into my arms instead of into my face.
That's one example.
It got to where, after a while, if we didn't, not that killing is something that you like to do,
But that was our job.
And the training that we went through, we were supposed to be, we were there to kill the enemy.
What time of day was the most active for y'all?
Oh, nighttime.
Always nighttime.
How would you describe the Vietnam spiders?
I mean, the Viet Cong spiders.
Very good.
Excellent.
As far as jungle fighting, open fighting, I don't think they would probably be as good as the American.
But as far as jungle fighting, probably just as good as the Japanese in World War II, if not better.
Who did you receive your orders from?
And by that I mean, where did they originate from?
Sink Pack Fleet.
And who's commander of that?
Maybe many.
Admiral?
Station in Hawaii?
I don't know.
I can't remember the guys.
I'm real bad on names.
He was commander of what again?
What was it?
The Pacific Fleet.
Okay.
What is your opinion about careerism in the military during Vietnam?
Did it exist in your opinion?
And by that I mean the commanding officers being there just as kind of a plus on their record.
I don't think we had, I don't think that the guys that went over there, you mean as young officers wanting to make a career?
I mean, up to generals and stuff like that.
The records that I've seen, at least in the Marines and stuff, were that there were only like three generals killed and two of them were in accidents.
And so, I mean, it was mainly, you know, the GIs that were up there fighting, doing the fighting, and the generals were, you know, off somewhere in a secure place.
Well, that's as in all wars.
You know, how many generals were killed in World War II?
On World War I, the general is not there to get out and pull the trigger.
It's just like the idea of a manager somewhere.
It's not what he can do.
It's what he can get others to do for him.
So I have absolutely no problem with the number of high-ranking officers that were killed because that's not their job.
Their job is to think, and our job was the job to, you know.
Did you respect your leaders?
I did, yes.
Okay.
Tell me about the role the Russians played in the war, based on what you saw.
Well, we went very far north, and I guess contrary to popular belief that, you know,
The North Vietnamese were actually fighting two fronts.
They were fighting aggression from the Chinese on one front.
And that's only because the North Vietnamese, which was stupid, they became aggressive to the Chinese.
And the Chinese weren't going to put up with that.
and then against the American in the South Vietnamese.
On the other front, the Russians not only supplies, I never saw actual troops flooding in, but they did have military advisors.
Advisors in the north?
Oh, yeah, training.
you know, in weaponry.
And just like we do when we go in somewhere, just like it started in Vietnam with us, you know, we sent in military advisors.
Of course, the Russians never had to pull troops into Vietnam as we did because they had the advantage.
They knew what they were fighting for.
They were fighting to take over South Vietnam and make Vietnam a communistic-run country, and they kept that idea.
We went in with the idea of freeing Vietnam, and we lost it somewhere.
The Russians, as far as instilling into the minds of the people, they did a real good job.
You had told me that you killed a Russian advisor.
That was the highlight of your time there.
Tell me about that.
Well, we went in just to get some documents, some maps,
We got a lot of our information on transportation routes, troop movements, mine areas, from what we could steal from the Viet Cong.
And we just went in to get some information
military advisor was there, and he just happened to wake up at the wrong time.
So it was, and it's not the idea of killing a Russian.
I guess I really wanted to kill an idea.
Because to me that they represent
communism and socialism to the fullest extent.
And if I could do anything to smash that idea, I was that much more ahead.
That was probably the highlight of my Vietnam experience anyway.
I can't say that it was fun.
Taking the life of another human being is not fun.
But it sure made it a lot easier knowing who he was.
Tell me about the day that you were wounded.
It was a mistake on our part because we went in to observe a lot of troop movement and we never
Got into open area.
And I don't know how it happened that day, but we were walking right out in the middle of a rice field.
And, I mean, snipers were always, I mean, always killing our guys.
Not the SEALs, but American troops.
I mean, the snipers were real, real good at what they did.
And we probably lost more lives from snipers than anything else.
from bombs or fire fights or anything.
Snipers probably kills most of our men.
But all of a sudden we heard shots fired and the CO went down.
And we just started firing everywhere.
I did a stupid thing as I went to
I went to get Garcia.
And when I was about halfway to him, we heard shots again.
And I was running.
And I got hit in the leg, in the ankle first, and then the leg.
And he just kept firing.
The other guys got his location, and we called out to a ship that was out in the harbor.
And he fired in and blew the tree that this sniper was in.
Just blew it with a five-inch gun.
Just blew it all.
It went up in a pile of smoke.
But by that time, I had already been pretty much wasted by then.
They got me out.
The CO had been shot in the head.
He was dead.
But they got me out.
Where else did you have wounds?
Besides your leg, anyone?
Stomach, shoulder, and arm.
And what happened to the guy that was shooting you?
Well, I'm sure he's dead.
They found pieces of the arm.
The other guy found just the pieces of the rifle that he was using, an AK-47, which is a real well-made Russian weapon.
And we reconstructed it and dedicated it to the ship that fired the round.
So they hung it up in their galley in a glass case.
Tell me about the day that you were captured.
Oh, that was a joke.
We got information that we were supposed to go in and, again, just make observations and see who was there, how many, the strength of the Viet Cong.
We went in and found out it was American Fifth Army was in there.
So we just walked in.
Well, they thought we were, you have to understand, I understand their motives for taking us prisoners.
They thought we were spies.
Because we don't carry any, SEALs don't carry any ID.
You know, they're going in.
What sort of uniform did you wear?
Normally a black turtleneck sweater with black gabardine pants and jungle boots and as many explosives and weapons as we could.
Why didn't they recognize you as Americans?
Well, there are no markings or anything.
You don't have any kind of markings on you at all as to manufacturer or anything.
So as far as they knew, what had happened is in between the time when we got our orders to go in, the North Viet Cong had backed off.
And Fifth Army had moved in to the position where the Viet Cong were supposed to have been.
So when we went in there, you know, we just found the Fifth Army and walked in and we could have, you know, been spies or... Russian spies.
Russians.
Or just about anybody.
So I understand.
How long were you held and what did it take to get you released?
Well, it got a little aggravating.
After 10 days, we became pretty upset.
They treated us real well.
They kept joking around about sending us over to the Koreans.
The Koreans are probably the best people to get information out of prisoners of war.
Finally, the admiral that was aboard, I can't remember which carrier it was, one of the carriers that was there, admiral that was aboard that carrier, had to come in in ideas to get us out.
It took 10 days?
Actually, it was like 15 days in total.
But they treated us well.
They fed us real good.
It was mainly the heckling.
They were giving us a hard time.
They sincerely believed that you were Russians?
I'm not sure.
They had some wacko officers in there.
You've got to understand the Army.
I don't know if they...
thought it was a joke.
To us, it wasn't a very good joke because we still had a job to do.
If they would have really been sincere about turning us over to the Koreans, there probably would have been a few of them taken out in the attempt.
Okay, tell me some more about some other operations you went on.
Any other incidents like that?
Did you ever come close to getting captured by the North Vietnamese?
Oh, no.
No.
It may sound funny, but you need to understand that
that when you're in a fighting group like this, that you're just kind of like a machine, you know.
We had gone up against 30, 40 at a time here in Conk, and it was killing.
You know, so the...
The odds were always in our favor.
They were real sneaky in jungle maneuvers, but so were we.
Over the regular GI Joe that goes in, they had the advantage.
The Army, the Marine Corps,
did not really train enough in jungle.
And we still don't train today enough in jungle warfare.
If we get into a conflict in Central America, our men are still going to be not equipped in jungle warfare.
And we do not spend enough time.
We're so ancient.
You send a guy in with 100 pounds on his back, a shovel and a pick and all this junk on his back that is useless in jungle warfare.
You can't do that to a man.
You take a North Vietnamese capture,
which was rare, because they'd just rather die than be captured.
But the ones that were captured, they'd have just a handful of rice and just as many weapons as they could carry.
We'd load our guys down in jungle warfare.
You can't do that.
We're just behind the times.
We started blowing our troops out around 1972, and you stayed until 74.
Why was that?
Well, I remember like in 1970, 1972, we mined Haiphong Harbor, President Nixon did, to cut off supplies to the North Vietnamese, the ships that were going in.
So militarily, we were still, just because we started pulling out a few troops, there were always troops coming back and forth.
And I'm not going to say it was a hype put over by the press or even the White House, but we were pretty much still at full strength over there.
We weren't in full enough strength to get the job done.
Did you receive any medals when you were in Vietnam?
Yeah.
Yeah, I got a few.
How do you view them?
I'm very, well, I'll put it this way.
I'm very proud of the uniform that I wore and it doesn't bother me a bit to put it on in Veterans Day and Memorial Day.
The medals that are on it are to me just a recognition of a job well done.
They might be
given by the military.
I have a presidential citation that I got from President Nixon.
But I'm proud of him.
I did the best that I could do to stamp out what I hate the most.
If our government wants to give me a medal to pin on my chest because of it, then I'll accept that.
Why do you think we lost the war in Vietnam?
If you were to place the blame on somebody, who would you place it on?
The American public.
I think the attitude of the American public
lost the war in Vietnam.
Did you feel we were justified in going over there in the first place?
Definitely.
I think any time a government asks us to come in because they feel a threat of communism in their back door, it justifies it.
Any other reasons why you thought we lost the war?
Anything to do with the military tactics you used?
failures in command or anything?
Did you feel like the South Vietnamese people had a real desire to fight the North Vietnamese?
Oh, definitely.
They still do.
There's still a war going on in Vietnam.
The majority, I think the majority of the South Vietnamese that I came in contact with
just a few that I did, but you can talk to them.
I went to Washington D.C. two years ago and there was a big delegation of South Vietnamese people there.
They were having a big rally there to
anti-establishment, anti-involvement in Central America.
And they were comparing our involvement in Central America to our involvement in Vietnam, which is unfair.
And there were a lot of Vietnamese people there that as military, they
They didn't have anything to do with the people that were protesting against our involvement because they appreciated what we did for them.
And it was a sincere appreciation of what we were there for.
They couldn't do it on their own.
They asked us for help.
We went in and helped them as much as we could.
The attitude of the American people, especially when it gets back to the GI, the guy that's fighting, you know,
And I have to compare it to World War II, because what else do we have to compare it with?

How do you think it would have went over if everything that the guys over there were fighting about, if everything that they heard was negative, that they were dogs and they were pigs and they were baby killers?
We had no business there.
No, the American people in World War II backed what we were doing because of the aggression of Hitler.
Hitler was not communist, but the idea of his aggression is what we were trying to stamp out, taking over other people's.
I think it was the letdown, you know, when you get bombarded and that's all you hear is how the American people dislike what you're doing.
It gives you a real insecure sense, you know, feeling.
And that's what we got when we were in Vietnam was, you know, college students protesting.
guys going on military trial for doing a job that they were sent to do.
It was real hard to come back to the United States with a sense of job well done.
I mean, nobody has ever said thank you for protecting
my liberties.
Continued on side two.
